msgid ""
"``_add_newdoc_ufunc(ufunc, newdoc)`` has been removed in favor of ``ufunc."
"__doc__ = newdoc``. (deprecated since 2.2)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:202
msgid "(`gh-30614 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30614>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:206
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:209
msgid "``linalg.eig`` and ``linalg.eigvals`` now always return complex arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:210
msgid ""
"Previously, the return values depended on whether the eigenvalues happen to "
"lie on the real line (which, for a general, non-symmetric matrix, is not "
"guaranteed)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:214
msgid ""
"This change makes consistent what was a value-dependent result. To retain "
"the previous behavior, do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:217
msgid ""
"w = eigvals(a)\n"
"if np.any(w.imag == 0):  # this is what NumPy used to do\n"
"    w = w.real"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:221
msgid ""
"If your matrix is symmetrix/hermitian, use ``eigh`` and ``eigvalsh`` instead "
"of ``eig`` and ``eigvals``. These are guaranteed to return real values. A "
"common case is covariance matrices, which are symmetric and positive "
"definite by construction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:226
msgid "(`gh-30411 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30411>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:229
msgid "MSVC support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:230
msgid ""
"NumPy now requires minimum MSVC 19.35 toolchain version on Windows "
"platforms. This corresponds to Visual Studio 2022 version 17.5 Preview 2 or "
"newer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:233
msgid "(`gh-30489 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30489>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:236
msgid "Cython support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:237
msgid ""
"NumPy's Cython headers (accessed via ``cimport numpy``) now require Cython "
"3.0 or newer to build. If you try to compile a project that depends on "
"NumPy's Cython headers using Cython 0.29 or older, you will see a message "
"like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:241
msgid ""
"Error compiling Cython file:\n"
"------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"...\n"
"# versions.\n"
"#\n"
"# See __init__.cython-30.pxd for the real Cython header\n"
"#\n"
"\n"
"DEF err = int('Build aborted: the NumPy Cython headers require Cython 3.0.0 "
"or newer.')\n"
"  ------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"\n"
"  /path/to/site-packages/numpy/__init__.pxd:11:13: Error in compile-time "
"expression:\n"
"  ValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10:\n"
"  'Build aborted: the NumPy Cython headers require Cython 3.0.0 or newer.'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:257
msgid ""
"Note that the invalid integer is not a bug in NumPy - we are intentionally "
"generating this error to avoid triggering a more obscure error later in the "
"build when an older Cython version tries to use a Cython feature that was "
"not available in the old Cython version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:262
msgid "(`gh-30770 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30770>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:265
msgid "``numpy.where`` no longer truncates Python integers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:267
msgid ""
"Previously, if the ``x`` or ``y`` argument of ``numpy.where`` was a Python "
"integer that was out of range of the output type, it would be silently "
"truncated.  Now, an ``OverflowError`` will be raised instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:271
msgid ""
"This change also applies to the underlying C API function ``PyArray_Where``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:273
msgid "(`gh-30803 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30803>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:276
msgid "Default memory allocator change"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:277
msgid ""
"NumPy now uses ``PyMem_RawMalloc`` and ``PyMem_RawFree`` as the default "
"memory allocator, instead of system's ``malloc`` and ``free`` directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:280 ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:474
msgid "(`gh-30846 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30846>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:283
msgid "``from_dlpack`` raises ``BufferError`` instead of ``RuntimeError``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:284
msgid ""
"``np.from_dlpack`` now raises ``BufferError`` instead of ``RuntimeError`` "
"when the incoming DLPack tensor has an unsupported device, dtype, or exceeds "
"the maximum number of dimensions. This aligns with the DLPack and Array API "
"specifications, which recommend ``BufferError`` for data that cannot be "
"imported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:290
msgid "(`gh-30937 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30937>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:293
msgid "Corrections to the BTPE binomial sampler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:294
msgid ""
"Two independent errors in the Stirling series of the acceptance/rejection "
"step of the BTPE algorithm used by ``numpy.random.Generator.binomial`` have "
"been corrected:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:298
msgid ""
"The third and fourth error terms were added rather than subtracted. This "
"sign error was inherited from section 5.3 of the original 1988 paper by "
"Kachitvichyanukul & Schmeiser, which incorrectly adds all four terms."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:302
msgid ""
"The leading coefficient had a digit-swap typo (``13680`` instead of "
"``13860``) that was introduced in the initial implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:305
msgid ""
"As a result, ``Generator.binomial`` and ``Generator.multinomial``, which "
"uses binomial internally, may now return different samples for the same seed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:308
msgid ""
"The legacy ``numpy.random.RandomState.binomial`` and ``numpy.random."
"RandomState.multinomial`` are not affected: they preserve the original "
"(incorrect) behavior, so existing streams remain reproducible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:312
msgid "(`gh-31238 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31238>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:315
msgid "``datetime64``/``timedelta64`` arithmetic raises on overflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:316
msgid ""
"Addition, subtraction, and integer multiplication of ``datetime64`` and "
"``timedelta64`` values now raise ``OverflowError`` when the result would "
"overflow ``int64`` or land on the ``NaT`` sentinel value.  Previously these "
"operations silently wrapped, often producing a value that was "
"indistinguishable from ``NaT``.  This matches the overflow checking already "
"performed by unit-conversion casts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:323
msgid "(`gh-31378 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31378>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:327
msgid "C API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:329
msgid ""
"It is now possible to register ``\"real\"`` and ``\"imag\"`` ArrayMethods "
"via ``PyUFunc_AddLoopsFromSpecs``.  These will be used for ``imag`` and "
"``real`` and should normally set ``*view_offset`` in their "
"``resolve_descriptors`` function to allow the array attributes to return "
"views."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:334 ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:619
msgid "(`gh-30984 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30984>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:336
msgid ""
"New ``PyDataType_TYPE``, ``PyDataType_KIND``, ``PyDataType_BYTEORDER`` and "
"``PyDataType_TYPEOBJ`` accessor macros to the C API. Together with the other "
"accessor macros added for the NumPy 2.0 transition, these allow accessing "
"the fields of ``PyArray_Descr`` structs without any direct field accesses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:341
msgid "(`gh-30994 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30994>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:343
msgid ""
"NumPy now supports the stable ABI for free-threaded Python as described in :"
"pep:`803`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:346
msgid "(`gh-31091 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31091>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:348
msgid ""
"``PyArray_DescrFromScalar`` now returns the full dtype descriptor for "
"scalars of user-defined parametric data types, including any dtype "
"parameters. Parameters were previously silently discarded, which could cause "
"incorrect results in operations like ``astype`` on scalar objects.  "
"Internally, the function now delegates to ``discover_descr_from_pyobject``, "
"which handles parametric dtypes correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:355
msgid "(`gh-31067 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31067>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:359
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:361
msgid ""
"It is now possible to register user-dtypes for dlpack export and import via "
"``numpy.dtypes.register_dlpack_dtype``. This functionality is meant to be "
"used with care by user-dtype authors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:365
msgid "(`gh-31256 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31256>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:368
msgid "Pixi package definitions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:369
msgid ""
"Pixi package definitions have been added for different kinds of from-source "
"builds of NumPy. These can be used in downstream Pixi workspaces via the "
"``pixi-build`` feature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:373
msgid ""
"Definitions for both ``default`` and AddressSanitizer-instrumented "
"(``asan``) builds are available in the source code under the ``pixi-packages/"
"`` directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:377
msgid "``linux-64`` and ``osx-arm64`` platforms are supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:379
msgid "(`gh-30381 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30381>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:382
msgid "``numpy.ndarray`` now supports structural pattern matching"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:383
msgid ""
"``numpy.ndarray`` and its subclasses now have the ``Py_TPFLAGS_SEQUENCE`` "
"flag set, enabling structural pattern matching (PEP 634) with ``match``/"
"``case`` statements. This also enables Cython to optimize integer indexing "
"operations. See :ref:``arrays.ndarray.pattern-matching`` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:388
msgid "(`gh-30653 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30653>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:391
msgid "Added N-D evaluation functions to the polynomial package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:392
msgid ""
"New functions ``polyvalnd``, ``chebvalnd``, ``legvalnd``, ``hermvalnd``, "
"``hermevalnd``, and ``lagvalnd`` have been added to evaluate polynomials in "
"arbitrary dimensions, analogous to the existing 2D and 3D evaluators."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:396
msgid "(`gh-30857 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30857>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:399
msgid ""
"New \"descending\" keyword argument for ``numpy.sort`` and ``numpy.argsort``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:400
msgid ""
"Users can now pass the ``descending=True`` keyword argument to ``numpy."
"sort`` and ``numpy.argsort`` to sort and argsort arrays in descending order. "
"NaN values, if present, are sorted to the end of the array in both ascending "
"and descending sorts. This feature is available for all built-in dtypes "
"except ``void``, ``object``, and ``generic``. Note that SIMD optimizations "
"for sorting are currently not available for descending sorts, so performance "
"may be slower."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:407
msgid "(`gh-31345 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31345>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:411
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:413
msgid ""
"For ``f2py``, the behaviour of ``intent(inplace)`` has improved.  "
"Previously, if an input array did not have the right dtype or order, the "
"input array was modified in-place, changing its dtype and replacing its data "
"by a corrected copy.  Now, instead, the corrected copy is kept a separate "
"array, which, after being passed and presumably modified by the fortran "
"routine, is copied back to the input routine.  The above means one no longer "
"has the risk that pre-existing views or slices of the input array start "
"pointing to unallocated memory (at the price of increased overhead for the "
"write-back copy at the end of the call)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:423
msgid ""
"A potential problem would be that one might get very different results if "
"one, e.g., previously passed in an integer array where a double array was "
"expected: the writeback to integer would likely give wrong results.  To "
"avoid such situations, ``intent(inplace)`` will now only allow arrays that "
"have equivalent type to that used in the fortran routine, i.e., ``dtype."
"kind`` is the same. For instance, a routine expecting double would be able "
"to receive float, but would raise on integer input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:431
msgid "(`gh-29929 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29929>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:434
msgid "``f2py`` modules now show allocatable arrays in ``dir()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:435
msgid ""
"Allocatable module variables wrapped by ``f2py`` now appear in ``dir()`` "
"output, matching their accessibility by name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:438
msgid "(`gh-30965 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30965>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:442
msgid "Performance improvements and changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:445
msgid "Improved performance of ``numpy.searchsorted``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:446
msgid ""
"The C++ binary search implementation used by ``numpy.searchsorted`` now has "
"a much better performance when searching for multiple keys. The new "
"implementation batches binary search steps across all keys to leverage cache "
"locality and out-of-order execution. Benchmarks show the new implementation "
"can be up to 20 times faster for hundreds of thousands keys while single-key "
"performance remains comparable to previous versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:453
msgid "(`gh-30517 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30517>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:456
msgid "Improved scaling of ufuncs on free-threading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:458
msgid ""
"NumPy's ufuncs now scale significantly better on free-threading builds of "
"CPython due to the following optimizations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:461
msgid ""
"**Lock-free dispatch table:** The ufuncs dispatch table is now implemented "
"as a lock-free concurrent hash map, allowing multiple threads to call ufuncs "
"without contention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:465
msgid ""
"**Immortal shared objects:** Certain shared objects, such as global memory "
"handlers, have been made immortal. This effectively reduces reference "
"counting contention across threads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:469
msgid ""
"**Optimized memory allocation:** NumPy now utilizes ``PyMem_RawMalloc`` and "
"``PyMem_RawFree`` for memory allocation. On Python 3.15 and newer, this "
"leverages ``mimalloc`` and significantly reduces memory allocation overhead "
"in multi-threaded workloads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:477
msgid "Faster reductions on small/medium contiguous arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:478
msgid ""
"``numpy.sum``, ``numpy.prod``, ``numpy.any``, ``numpy.all``, and other "
"reductions with an identity value now use a fast path when the input is a "
"contiguous, aligned, non-object array and the reduction covers all axes "
"(``axis=None``) with no special arguments. Typical speedup is ~1.3x on small "
"arrays; ``numpy.any`` / ``numpy.all`` on contiguous boolean arrays can see "
"speedup up to 1.9x."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:485
msgid "(`gh-31274 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31274>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:489
msgid "Typing improvements and changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:492
msgid ""
"``numpy.linalg`` typing improvements and preliminary shape-typing support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:493
msgid ""
"Input and output dtypes for ``numpy.linalg`` functions are now more precise. "
"Several of these functions also gain preliminary shape-typing support while "
"remaining backward compatible.  For example, the return type of ``numpy."
"linalg.matmul`` now depends on the shape-type of its inputs, or fall back to "
"the backward-compatible return type if the shape-types are unknown at type-"
"checking time. Because of limitations in Python's type system and current "
"type-checkers, shape-typing cannot cover every situation and is often only "
"implemented for the most common lower-rank cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:502
msgid "(`gh-30480 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30480>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:505
msgid "``numpy.ma`` typing annotations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:506
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.ma`` module is now fully covered by typing annotations.  This "
"includes annotations for masked arrays, masks, and various functions and "
"methods.  With this, NumPy has achieved 100% typing coverage across all its "
"submodules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:511
msgid "(`gh-30566 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30566>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:514
msgid "Shape-typing support for many functions and methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:515
msgid ""
"Many functions and methods now have shape-aware return type annotations. "
"Type-checkers can now infer the number of dimensions of the returned array "
"through common operations. For example, ``np.linspace(0, 1)`` is now typed "
"as a 1-d ``float64`` array, and ``np.sum(x, keepdims=True)`` has the same "
"number of dimensions as ``x``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:521
msgid ""
"This covers ``numpy.linalg`` functions, array creation functions (like "
"``asarray``, ``from{buffer,string,file,iter,regex}``), range functions "
"(``linspace``, ``logspace``, ``geomspace``), aggregation functions and "
"methods (``sum``, ``mean``, ``std``, ``var``, ``min``, ``max``, ``all``, "
"``any``, etc.), sorting (``sort``, ``argsort``, ``argpartition``), "
"cumulative operations (``cumsum``, ``cumprod``, etc.), set operations "
"(``unique_values``, ``intersect1d``, ``union1d``, etc.), and various other "
"functions including ``nonzero``, ``transpose``, ``diagonal``, "
"``atleast_{1,2,3}d``, ``clip``, ``round``, ``inner``, ``bincount``, and "
"``fft.fftfreq``. Several of these also gained more precise return dtype "
"annotations as part of this work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:532
msgid ""
"Shape-typing is still a work-in-progress, so coverage is not yet complete. "
"Because of limitations in Python's type system and current type-checkers, "
"shape-typing is often only implemented for the most common lower-rank cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:536
msgid "(`gh-31172 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31172>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:539
msgid "``numpy.fft`` typing improvements and preliminary shape-typing support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:540
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.fft`` functions now support non-``float64``/``complex128`` "
"dtypes and gain preliminary shape-typing support. For example, the return "
"type of ``numpy.fft.fft`` now depends on the shape-type of its inputs, "
"falling back to the backward-compatible return type when the shape-types are "
"unknown at type-checking time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:546
msgid "(`gh-31226 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31226>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:550
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:553
msgid "Structured array copies now use ``memcpy`` for contiguous dtypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:554
msgid ""
"Copying structured arrays with identical dtypes now uses ``memcpy`` instead "
"of field-by-field transfer when the dtype has a contiguous layout (no gaps "
"between fields). A new ``NPY_NOT_TRIVIALLY_COPYABLE`` dtype flag is set on "
"structured dtypes that have gaps in their memory layout, such as those "
"created with explicit ``offsets`` or via multi-field indexing. Only these "
"dtypes continue to use the slower field-by-field copy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:561
msgid ""
"This means that padding bytes in contiguous structured dtypes (e.g. those "
"created without explicit ``offsets``) may now be copied as part of the "
"``memcpy``, whereas previously they were left untouched. Code that relies on "
"padding bytes being preserved during structured array copies may be affected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:566
msgid "(`gh-29270 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29270>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:569
msgid "``numpy.ctypeslib.as_ctypes`` now does not support scalar types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:570
msgid ""
"The function ``numpy.ctypeslib.as_ctypes`` has been updated to only accept "
"``numpy.ndarray``.  Passing a scalar type (e.g., ``numpy.int32(5)``) will "
"now raise a ``TypeError``.  This change was made to avoid the issue "
"`gh-30354 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/30354>`__ and to enforce "
"the readonly nature of scalar types in NumPy.  The previous behavior relied "
"on undocumented implicit temporary arrays and was not well-defined.  Users "
"who need to convert scalar types to ctypes should first convert them to an "
"array (e.g., ``numpy.asarray``) before passing them to ``numpy.ctypeslib."
"as_ctypes``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:579 ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:588
msgid "(`gh-30538 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30538>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:582
msgid "``__array_interface__`` changes on scalars"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:583
msgid ""
"Scalars now export the ``__array_interface__`` directly rather than "
"including an array copy as a ``__ref`` entry. This means that scalars are "
"now exported as read-only while they previously exported as writeable.  The "
"path via ``__ref`` was undocumented and not consistently used even within "
"NumPy itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:591
msgid "``meshgrid`` now always returns a tuple"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:592
msgid ""
"``np.meshgrid`` previously used to return a list when ``sparse`` was true "
"and ``copy`` was false.  Now, it always returns a tuple regardless of the "
"arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:596
msgid "(`gh-30707 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30707>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:599
msgid "``numpy.triu_indices`` now accepts ``unsigned integers``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:600
msgid ""
"``numpy.triu_indices`` previously used to error in some cases when "
"``unsigned integers`` were given as arguments. Now, it accepts them in all "
"cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:606
msgid "``object`` dtype in ``.real`` and ``.imag`` and related functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:607
msgid ""
"The array attributes ``.real`` and ``.imag`` now behave differently for "
"object arrays and return ``getattr(element, \"real\", element)`` or "
"``getattr(element, \"imag\", 0)`` elementwise.  Additionally, the return for "
"both is now read-only to avoid possible in-place changes having no effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:612
msgid "This change also affects ``np.isreal()`` which uses ``arr.imag``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:614
msgid ""
"Previously, ``.imag`` always returned ``0`` while ``.real`` returned the "
"original array unmodified.  The new behavior now returnes the correct values "
"for complex Python objects but may also lead to surprises for example if "
"``element.real()`` is a method and not a property."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:622
msgid "NumPy's internal memory allocations now use ``PyMem_RawMalloc``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:623
msgid ""
"NumPy's internal memory allocations now use ``PyMem_RawMalloc`` instead of "
"``malloc`` and can be tracked by ``tracemalloc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/2.5.0-notes.rst:626
msgid "(`gh-31503 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31503>`__)"
msgstr ""
